{{Infobox climber | image = | caption = | name = Deshun Deysel | nationality = South Africa | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|4|9|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Uitenhage]], [[South Africa]] | death_date = | death_place = | typeofclimber = | highestgrade = | knownfor = | firstascents = | namedroutes = | majorascents = [[Mount Everest]] }}
'''Deshun Deysel''' (born 9 April 1970) is a South African mountaineer and businesswoman who was part of the first South African expedition to [[Mount Everest]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite news | author = Claire Keeton and Paul Ash | title = South Africans who made history on Everest | newspaper = Sunday Times | date = 29 May 2016 | pages = | url = http://www.timeslive.co.za/sundaytimes/stnews/2016/05/29/South-Africans-who-made-history-on-Everest | accessdate = 31 July 2016}}</ref> This was the first time the new South Africa flag was planted on top of the world. She has climbed some of the world's highest mountains in 14 expeditions over 5 continents in 15 years.
Known as a high altitude mountaineer, her career started out as a teacher. She has since developed into one of South Africa's leading motivational speakers during the past 20 years. Deshun is the founder and director of Deshun Deysel & Associates, a business that focuses on encouraging and equiping leadership in a context of change and diversity.<ref>{{cite news | author = Nazley Omar | title = Deshun Deysel on why it pays to persevere | publisher = Ndalo Media | date = 13 June 2016 | url = http://www.destinyconnect.com/2016/06/13/deshun-deysel-pays-persevere/ | accessdate = 31 July 2016}}</ref>
Deshun is Laureus Sports Ambassador since 2010<ref>{{cite news | author = | title = Oscar winner Kevin Spacey to host Laureus World Sports Awards | newspaper = AIPS | date = 8 March 2010 | pages = | url = http://www.aipsmedia.com/index.php?page=news&cod=4507 | accessdate = 31 July 2016}}</ref>
